  "description": "¶Entry conditions You should know the definition of a ring.\n¶Definitions An integral domain is a commutative ring with no zero divisors: if a⋅b=0a \\cdot b = 0 then a=0a = 0 or b=0b = 0. This means multiplication behaves as expected — you can cancel nonzero factors.\nA field is a commutative ring in which every nonzero element has a multiplicative inverse. Equivalently, a field is a commutative ring where the nonzero elements form an abelian group under multiplication.\n",
